  <p>Your topic’s information architecture is something that can and should be designed, tested and iterated via user-centred methods, just as you do with content and UI. It should form a key part of your discovery, design, development and maintenance process.</p>
  <h2>Discovery</h2>
  <p>During the Discovery phase, you need to find out about your users’ understanding of the topic you’re interested in. What are their mental models of the topic?</p>
  <p>"A mental model is an explanation of someone's thought process about how something works in the real world… Mental models can help shape behaviour and set an approach to solving problems... and doing tasks." (<a href="">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mental_model</a>)</p>
  <ul>
    <li>What words do they use and understand when describing the topic?</li>
    <li>How do they group and label the content within your topic?</li>
    <li>What are their Top Tasks for the topic? What are the most important things that they need to accomplish with your content?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>The IA research methods you choose will differ depending on a range of factors. How much the team already knows about your topic’s users, maturity of existing content, timeframes, risks, etc. Many IA research methods can be conducted in the same research sessions as those designed to uncover content needs.</p>
  <h3>Generative research methods for IA</h3>
  <h4>User interviews</h4>
  <p>To understand users’ mental models and vocabulary, finding strategies, and evaluate existing NHS.UK or competitor IAs.</p>
  <h4>Open card sorts</h4>
  <p>To understand users’ mental models of the topic, the vocabulary they use, and to generate ideas for how to structure and label content.</p>
  <h4>Search logs and analytics</h4>
  <p>To understand common on-site and Google searches and search terms associated with your topic - the vocabulary people use. To understand the performance and popularity of existing content. Are there any common searches that represent user needs that are currently unmet?</p>
  <h4>Tree tests</h4>
  <p>To benchmark existing or competitor IAs and understand what works and what doesn’t.</p>
  <h4>Prioritisation research</h4>
  <p>To understand which tasks are most important to the most users, in order to prioritise content and information structures, and to validate against.</p>
  <h4>Content audit</h4>
  <p>To understand what content already exists that is related to your topic. What conditions, treatments, lifestyle improvements, services or other content exists on NHS.UK and elsewhere that people interested in your topic might also care about? Does any content need to be culled? Is anything obviously missing?</p>
  <h3>Site-wide user needs matrix</h3>
  <p>IA rarely appears as a user need in user research as something explicit like “I’m looking for a hub page” or “What I need is a breadcrumb”. But poor IA does show up in research:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>People get lost and confused - they cannot orient themselves</li>
    <li>People can’t find what they need - they cannot navigate around or successfully search the content</li>
    <li>People can’t get back to things they were interested in - inconsistent structures do not support re-finding</li>
  </ul>
  <p>The key IA user needs of placemaking, orientation, navigation, search and consistency can be expressed as site-wide user needs, for everyone visiting NHS.UK.</p>
  <p>Read the <a href="">site-wide user needs matrix</a>.</p>

  <h2>Alpha and Beta</h2>
  <p>Design, test and iterate your topic’s information architecture alongside the content and UI.</p>
  <p>The information architecture of your topic can be expressed as a sitemap: a hierarchical diagram of every page of content included in the topic, showing the way they are grouped and labelled. That sitemap is then realised in the form of prototype hub pages, content pages and navigation structures. User research can be conducted on candidate sitemaps and prototypes at every stage, in order to learn and iterate. This IA design and testing happens alongside, and in conjunction with, content design and testing.</p>
  <h3>Site map design</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>List all the pages of content you need to provide for your topic</li>
    <li>Create a hierarchical site map diagram for your content</li>
      <ul>
        <li>Every page of content has a place in the site map - its canonical home</li>
        <li>Group and label the content to match users’ mental models of your topic and the vocabulary they use. The aim here is to provide a strong information scent to all content.</li>
        <li>Think about the breadth and depth of the site map. Too deep and the information scent may be weak for pages deep in the hierarchy. Too wide and users may struggle to select from too many options.</li>
      </ul>
        <li>Test your site map with users and iterate if necessary
      <ul>
        <li>If your site map tests poorly, think about whether the content groups and labels match your users’ understanding of your topic (their mental model). Have you provided a strong information scent to all content? Are there too many choices?</li>
      </ul>
  </ul>
