  <h3>Site map evaluation</h3>
  <p>You can test your site map with users before creating a prototype, to help you understand if your groups and labels work. The IA evaluation methods you choose will differ depending on your circumstances. You may choose to evaluate your IA only at prototype stage, rather than at sitemap stage. Or you may choose to do both. Again, it will depend on Discovery findings, the maturity of existing content, timeframes, risks, etc.</p>
  <h4>Closed card sorts</h4>
  <p>To understand if your chosen labels make sense to users, and how they would group your content under those labels.</p>
  <h4>Tree tests</h4>
  <p>To test whether people can follow the information scent provided by your site map to complete priority tasks for your content. If you benchmarked an existing IA during Discovery, you can test whether your new site map is an improvement.</p>
  <h3>Prototype design</h3>
  <p>There are templates for navigational hub pages and content pages in Wagtail. There are components documented in GitHub.<p>
  <p>They were designed by the IA team to support users’ needs for placemaking, orientation, navigation and consistency. They are also designed to support users in different information-seeking modes.</p>
  <p>They were all designed, tested and iterated mobile-first and have been found to be usable, robust and flexible. The page templates and components were were designed to work as a coherent whole, not individually in isolation. These templates were first used to build the Coronavirus hub. But there’s more to do: the IA team is collaborating with teams across NHS.UK to stress-test and extend the system to cover all our content.</p>
