  <h4>Hub pages</h4>
  <p>Hub pages are designed to do one thing well: to route people to the content they need. Not to provide that content. They provide consistent navigation structures to allow users to browse to their destination, discover content they didn’t know they needed and re-find information without getting lost.</p>
  <ul>
    <li>They show users where they are and where else they might go</li>
    <li>They showcase all content and related links for any given topic or sub-topic</li>
    <li>They allow you to promote up to three ‘top tasks’ for your topic, allowing you to provide shortcuts to popular content that would otherwise be ‘buried’ in your site map hierarchy</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Each ‘parent’ page in your site map represents a ‘hub’ page in your prototype. Your ‘hub’ page will list all the ‘child’ pages of the ‘parent’ page. These ‘child’ pages can be a mix of further hubs and/or content pages.</p>
  <p>There are two different hub page templates - Level 1 Hub and Level 2 Hub. This allows the design to change as users move through the content. Level 1 Hubs are used for larger groups of content, for example a group of conditions like Diabetes or a group of medicines like Antihistamines. Individual conditions or medicines are served by Level 2 Hubs. Larger topics may need additional hub levels and design for this is still a work in progress.</p>
  <h4>Content pages</h4>
  <p>Our content pages are designed to:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Allow users to ascertain if they are in the right place, and:</li>
      <ul>
        <li>if so, read the content there</li>
        <li>if not, get to the right place</li>
      </ul>
    <li>Facilitate the discovery of additional content within the topic</li>
    <li>Ensure there are no ‘dead ends’ if they want to continue their journey</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Content pages provide breadcrumbs (to go up to ‘parent’ pages), headings, and page-to-page (‘sibling’) navigation. Our hub and content pages work together to provide a consistent navigation system across the whole of NHS.UK.</p>
  <h3>Prototype testing</h3>
  <p>When testing a prototype, you are testing the IA, content and UI all together. It is sometimes tricky to identify an IA problem as separate from a content problem. However, if people get lost, it might well be an IA problem. Are the topic groupings wrong? Are the topic labels providing a poor information scent, in that people are looking for specific words or phrases but not finding them?</p>
  <h4>First-click testing</h4>
  <p>To understand if your users can quickly and easily find what they’re looking for when they land on your topic. Can be used on full designs or early sketches to test approach and visual prioritisation. (Unlike tree testing, which provides no visual hierarchy.)</p>
  <h4>Usability testing</h4>
  <p>To understand whether your users can find the content they need. Does the prototype meet the site-wide user needs, as well as your topic user needs? Can users follow an information scent to complete key tasks? If not, why not?</p>
  <p>Explicitly testing an IA is odd in that you can’t expect users to notice or comment on page furniture or navigation structures. We can’t ask them to tell us ‘where they are’ on the website as that may be a meaningless question to them. Instead, we set them tasks that they will be able to complete if the IA is doing its job, albeit invisibly. We set tasks that ask them to move down, up and sideways around our site map, and observe how easily or otherwise they can move around.</p>


